How would you fix the error swallowing in this HTML parser code?

// src/language-html/parse/parse.js:32
const result = parser.parse(source);
if (result.errors && result.errors.length > 0) {
  throw result.errors[0];  // silently discards errors[1..n]
}

output:
The problem: only the first parse error is thrown, silently discarding all subsequent errors. Users see one error, fix it, re-run, and hit the next error — a frustrating round-trip experience.

Fix — report all errors in a single aggregated error:

```javascript
class AggregateParseError extends Error {
  constructor(errors) {
    super(`${errors.length} parse error${
      errors.length > 1 ? 's' : ''
    }:\n${errors.map((e, i) => `  ${i + 1}. ${e.message}`).join('\n')}`);
    this.errors = errors;
  }
}

if (result.errors && result.errors.length > 0) {
  throw new AggregateParseError(result.errors);
}
```

This gives users the full picture in one run. The `errors` array is preserved on the custom error for programmatic consumers who need individual error details.

