How would you refactor a 200+ line switch statement in a GraphQL printer that dispatches on `node.kind`?

// src/language-graphql/printer-graphql.js:20
function genericPrint(path, options, print) {
  const node = path.getValue();
  switch (node.kind) {
    case 'Document': /* 15 lines */ break;
    case 'OperationDefinition': /* 20 lines */ break;
    case 'Field': /* 12 lines */ break;
    // ... 15+ more cases
  }
}

output:
Same Strategy pattern approach as YAML, but with a TypeScript-friendly twist for GraphQL's `Kind` enum:

```typescript
import { Kind } from 'graphql';

type PrintHandler = (path: AstPath, options: Options, print: PrintFn) => Doc;

const graphqlPrinters: Record<Kind, PrintHandler> = {
  [Kind.DOCUMENT]: printDocument,
  [Kind.OPERATION_DEFINITION]: printOperationDefinition,
  [Kind.FIELD]: printField,
  // ... one per kind
};

function genericPrint(path: AstPath, options: Options, print: PrintFn): Doc {
  const node = path.getValue();
  const handler = graphqlPrinters[node.kind];
  if (!handler) {
    throw new Error(`Unsupported GraphQL node kind: ${node.kind}`);
  }
  return handler(path, options, print);
}
```

With TypeScript's `Record<Kind, PrintHandler>`, you get compile-time exhaustiveness checking — the compiler will error if you add a new `Kind` but forget to add a handler. This is safer than a switch statement that silently falls through to default.

